description: Adam Haney will be discussing approaches for test driven development in Django. This includes techniques for testing models, forms, form wizards, views and templates. We'll also discuss Python's Mock library and how mocking and stubbing can be used to isolate test cases.

name: Using knowledge systems to automatically address system problems
description: Josh Marlow has been working on 'Django Narrative' a system that has the ability to identify issues as they arise and help developers and support staff to diagnose problems that are data or system related.

name: Developing applications in a Vagrant environment
description: Micah Hausler will be explaining how to use Vagrant for local development that mimics a production environment</p>

name: Thinking in Objects
description: Anthony Blardo will be going over his philosophy for creating good object oriented code. Instead of simply covering basic OO concepts this talk discusses a state of mind for development.

name: An overview of Angular.js

Handling Time Zones and Recurrences like a Boss in Python/Django w/ Wes Kendall
description: Doing datetime manipulation in Python can be a very tedious task, especially across different time zones and daylight savings time boundaries. This talk summarizes a new open-source library called "Fleming" that aids in doing datetime manipulation across timezones. It also talks about "Django Localized Recurrence", another new open-source library for scheduling recurrences of events based on a time zone. The talk also gives a basic introduction to pytz in Python and some of the ways that Django handles time zones.

name: How economics effects developers w/ Rodger Maarfi
An Introduction to Adaptive Design w/ Aaron Gustafson
description:
For years, designers and developers have griped about the difficulties they encountered in supporting the numerous desktop browsers out there, but mobile is even more fragmented. Phones, tablets, media players, video game systems—each device (and in some cases each browser on each device) has its own dimensions, quirks and capabilities. It can make your brain hurt just thinking about it.

Thankfully, going mobile doesn’t have to be a painful experience. In this session, Aaron Gustafson will introduce you to the concept of progressive enhancement and demonstrate why it is the way forward for web design, especially on mobile devices. In the course of his talk, he’ll walk you through progressive enhancement’s layered approach and show you how the latest techniques—mobile first, responsive design, and adaptive UI—fit in to the process.

name: Continuous Integration and Deployment @Bellhops w/ Adam Haney
description: Several developers have asked about tools and process for bringing continuous integration into their organization. I'd love to give an overview of how Bellhops does continuous integration and deployment and also highlight tools that are available.

name: Useful, Usable & Desirable: Designing for People w/ Jessica Ivins
description:
"It needs to be easy to use." We've heard this many times before from stakeholders, clients, and colleagues. But how do you go about making a website—or any product or service—easy to use? While there are plenty of industry leaders, books, articles, and best practices to learn from, what matters is context. For whom are you designing? What is this person's goals, motivations, and pain points? What is he or she trying to accomplish? Good design solves real problems. It doesn't just decorate. How can you design to solve real problems for real people?

This session will explore the fundamentals of user experience. We'll explore industry best practices and examples of websites that solve real problems for real people. There are many tools and disciplines within user experience, from content strategy to information architecture to user research. By understanding these tools and when to use them, and by understanding the context of each design problem we are faced with, we can begin to understand how to utilize design thinking and creating user experiences that are useful, usable, and desirable.

name: Like webscale but over 9000: Introduction to elixir and erlang
description: Erlang has been behind some of the most reliable systems ever built.  Elixir is a new language that seeks to combine that same performance with the power of a dynamic language.  In this talk we'll go over the basics of Elixir, functional concepts, and demonstrate how easy it is to build large scale, reliable systems on the Erlang VM.

description: So you know the basics of Git, but there is so much more that just creating repositories, adding and committing changes, and pushing and pulling changes to remote repositories. Through this session I hope to teach you some tips and tricks as well as best practices to help you get the most of out Git and work better as a team.

How to get started, some best practices, and common mistakes. Further reading - Sass: http://sass-lang.com . Less: http://lesscss.org/

name: Falling in Love with Forms w/ Aaron Gustafson
description:
In this session, we will explore forms from top to bottom, examining how they work and how their components can be incorporated with other elements to maximize accessibility, improve semantics, and allow for more flexible styling. You’ll get to see the complete picture with forms, including:


* new HTML5 field types;

* validation, error messages & formatting hints;

* how to mark up and style forms for the greatest flexibility in responsive designs; and

* best practices for enhancing forms with JavaScript.

name: So long, jQuery, and thanks for all the fish! w/ Matt Turnure
description: If you can't make this event, catch it streaming here: https://plus.google.com/b/103401260409601780643/events/cr4c6cb96aartv677su6mb6jkn8

name: Telling local stories with data viz and d3.js w/ Mary Helen Miller
description:
D3.js is a javascript library, created by a developer at the New York Times. It’s a powerful tool for manipulating the document object model and creating beautiful data visualizations, in journalism and beyond.

Come learn about how D3 can be used. I’ll show you a range of projects that use D3, including a few projects that I’ve created for the Chattanooga Times Free Press. We’ll talk about how data visualizations can help us ask better questions and tell better stories about our community.

Remember if you can't make it this  week, you can catch it on YouTube here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mk0XwRqpitU
